Question 1

  1. Define \[ b_{ij}=(\mathbf x_i-\bar{\mathbf x})^\top (\mathbf x_j-\bar{\mathbf x}), \quad i,j=1, \ldots , n, \] and write \(\mathbf B=(b_{ij})_{i,j=1}^n\). Prove that \[\mathbf B=(\mathbf H\mathbf X)(\mathbf H\mathbf X)^\top,\] where \(\mathbf H\) is the \(n \times n\) centering matrix and \(\mathbf X= (\mathbf x_1, \ldots , \mathbf x_n)^\top\) is the data matrix.
Solution

We have seen previously that \[ \mathbf H\mathbf X= \begin{pmatrix} (\mathbf x_1-\bar{\mathbf x})^\top \\...\\...\\(\mathbf x_n -\bar{\mathbf x})^\top \end{pmatrix}, \] so \[\begin{align*} \mathbf H\mathbf X(\mathbf H\mathbf X)^\top &=\begin{pmatrix} (\mathbf x_1-\bar{\mathbf x})^\top \\...\\...\\(\mathbf x_n -\bar{\mathbf x})^\top \end{pmatrix}(\mathbf x_1 -\bar{\mathbf x}, \ldots , \mathbf x_n -\bar{\mathbf x})\\ &=\begin{pmatrix} (\mathbf x_1 -\bar{\mathbf x})^\top (\mathbf x_1 -\bar{\mathbf x}) &... & ...& ...&(\mathbf x_1-\bar{\mathbf x})^\top (\mathbf x_n -\bar{\mathbf x})\\ ...&... &... &...&...\\ ...&... &...&...&...\\ ...&... &...&...&...\\ (\mathbf x_n-\bar{\mathbf x})^\top (\mathbf x_1-\bar{\mathbf x})&...&...&...&(\mathbf x_n-\bar{\mathbf x}^\top (\mathbf x_n-\bar{\mathbf x}) \end{pmatrix}\\ &=(b_{ij})_{i,j=1}^n =\mathbf B, \end{align*}\] as required.

  1. Show that \(\mathbf B\) is positive semi-definite, i.e., explain why, for all \(n \times 1\) vectors \(\mathbf a\), \[ \mathbf a^\top \mathbf B\mathbf a=\mathbf a^\top (\mathbf H\mathbf X) (\mathbf H\mathbf X)^\top \mathbf a\geq 0. \]
Solution

From part i., \[\begin{align*} \mathbf a^\top \mathbf B\mathbf a&=\mathbf a^\top \mathbf H\mathbf X(\mathbf H\mathbf X)^\top \mathbf a\\ &=\mathbf a^\top \mathbf H\mathbf X\mathbf X^\top \mathbf H^\top \mathbf a\\ &=\mathbf b^\top \mathbf b=\sum_{i=1}^n b_i^2 \geq 0, \end{align*}\] where \(\mathbf b=(b_1, \ldots , b_n)^\top\) is the vector \(\mathbf b=\mathbf X^\top \mathbf H^\top \mathbf a\). This holds for any \(\mathbf a\), and consequently \(\mathbf B\) is positive semi-definite.

Question 2

  1. Prove that if \(\mathbf A\) is a symmetric \(n \times n\) matrix, then \[\mathbf B= \mathbf H\mathbf A\mathbf H\] has elements given by \[ b_{ij}=a_{ij}-\bar{a}_{i+}-\bar{a}_{+j}+\bar{a}_{++}, \qquad i,j=1, \ldots , n, \] where
    \[\bar{a}_{i+}= \frac{1}{n} \sum_{j=1}^n a_{ij}, \quad \bar{a}_{+j}=\frac{1}{n} \sum_{i=1}^n a_{ij}, \quad\mbox{and} \quad\bar{a}_{++} = \frac{1}{n^2} \sum_{i,j=1}^n a_{ij}.\]
Solution

Suppose \(\mathbf A\) is a symmetric \(n \times n\) matrix. Then \[\begin{align} \mathbf B&=\mathbf H\mathbf A\mathbf H\nonumber\\ &=(\mathbf I_n -n^{-1}{\bf 1}_n {\bf 1}_n^\top )\mathbf A(\mathbf I_n -n^{-1}{\bf 1}_n {\bf 1}_n^\top )\nonumber\\ &=\mathbf A-{\bf 1}_n (n^{-1}{\bf 1}_n^\top \mathbf A)-(n^{-1}\mathbf A{\bf 1}_n){\bf 1}_n^\top -{\bf 1}_n(n^{-2}{\bf 1}_n^\top \mathbf A{\bf 1}_n) {\bf 1}_n^\top \nonumber\\ &=\mathbf A-{\bf 1}_n \bar{\mathbf a}_+^\top -\bar{\mathbf a}_+ {\bf 1}_n^\top +\bar{a}_{++} {\bf 1}_n {\bf 1}_n^\top, \label{matrixformB} \end{align}\] where \[\bar{\mathbf a}_+ \equiv (\bar{a}_{1+}, \ldots , \bar{a}_{n+})^\top =n^{-1}\mathbf A{\bf 1}_n=(n^{-1}{\bf 1}^\top \mathbf A)^\top, \qquad \bar{a}_{i+}=n^{-1}\sum_{j=1} a_{ij} \] and \[ \bar{a}_{++}=n^{-2}\sum_{i,j=1}^n a_{ij}. \] Consequently, \[\begin{equation} b_{ij}=a_{ij}-\bar{a}_{i+}-\bar{a}_{+j}+\bar{a}_{++} \qquad i,j=1, \ldots , n, \label{bij} \end{equation}\] where, by symmetry of \(\mathbf A\), \(\bar{a}_{+j}=\bar{a}_{j+}\).

  1. Assume that \(\mathbf B\) is positive semi-definite with \(k\) strictly positive eigenvalues and let \[ \mathbf B= \sum_{j=1}^k \lambda_j \mathbf u_j\mathbf u_j^\top =\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda\mathbf U^\top, \] where \(\boldsymbol \Lambda=\text{diag}\{\lambda_1, \ldots , \lambda_k\}\) and \(\mathbf U\) is \(n \times k\) and satisfies \(\mathbf U^\top \mathbf U=\mathbf I_k\). Now define a ‘new’ \(n \times k\) data matrix \[ \mathbf X=[\mathbf x_1, \ldots , \mathbf x_n]^\top=\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{1/2}. \] Show that \(b_{ij}=\mathbf x_i^\top \mathbf x_j\) for all \(i,j=1, \ldots , n\).
    Hint: check that for \(\mathbf X\) defined as above, \(\mathbf X\mathbf X^\top =\mathbf B\).
Solution

We have \[\begin{align*} \mathbf X\mathbf X^\top &=\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{1/2} (\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{1/2})^\top\\ &=\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda^{1/2} \boldsymbol \Lambda^{1/2}\mathbf U^\top =\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda\mathbf U^\top = \mathbf B. \end{align*}\] So \[\begin{align*} \mathbf B&=\mathbf X\mathbf X^\top\\ &=\begin{pmatrix} \mathbf x_1^\top \\...\\...\\...\\\mathbf x_n^\top \end{pmatrix}(\mathbf x_1, \ldots , \mathbf x_n)\\ &=\begin{pmatrix} \mathbf x_1^\top \mathbf x_n &...&...&...&\mathbf x_1^\top \mathbf x_n\\ ...&...&...&...&...\\ ...&...&...&...&...\\ ...&...&...&...&...\\ \mathbf x_n^\top \mathbf x_1 &...&...&...&\mathbf x_n^\top \mathbf x_n, \end{pmatrix} \end{align*}\] and consequently \(b_{ij}=\mathbf x_i^\top \mathbf x_j\), as required.

  1. We now need to show that \(\mathbf D=(d_{ij})\) represents the set of inter-point distances for this new data matrix. Recall that \(a_{ij}=-d_{ij}^2/2\). Deduce that \[ (\mathbf x_i -\mathbf x_j)^\top (\mathbf x_i-\mathbf x_j)= b_{ii} + b_{jj}-2b_{ij}; \] and so, using the first part of this question, show that \[ (\mathbf x_i -\mathbf x_j)^\top (\mathbf x_i-\mathbf x_j)=-2a_{ij}=d_{ij}^2. \] Hence the new inter-point distances are the same as the original ones.
Solution

Using part (b) of this question, \[\begin{align} b_{ii}+b_{jj}-2b_{ij}&=\mathbf x_i^\top \mathbf x_i +\mathbf x_j^\top \mathbf x_j-\mathbf x_i^\top \mathbf x_j - \mathbf x_j^\top \mathbf x_i \nonumber \\ &=(\mathbf x_i-\mathbf x_j)^\top (\mathbf x_i-\mathbf x_j). \label{biijj} \end{align}\]

Substituting for \(b_{ij}\) on the LHS, we obtain \[\begin{align} (\mathbf x_i-\mathbf x_j)^\top (\mathbf x_i-\mathbf x_j)&=b_{ii}+b_{jj}-2b_{ij}\\ &= a_{ii}-2\bar{a}_{i+}+\bar{a}_{++} +a_{jj}-2\bar{a}_{j+}+\bar{a}_{++}\\ & \qquad - 2(a_{ij}-\bar{a}_{i+}-\bar{a}_{+j}+\bar{a}_{++})\\ &=a_{ii}+a_{jj}-2a_{ij}. \label{aiijj} \end{align}\] Moreover, if we write \(a_{ij}=-d_{ij}^2/2\), with \(a_{ii}=a_{jj}=0\), then \[ (\mathbf x_i-\mathbf x_j)^\top (\mathbf x_i -\mathbf x_j)=-2a_{ij}=d_{ij}^2. \] Consequently, the inter-point distances of the new points \(\mathbf x_1, \ldots ,\mathbf x_n\) are given by the original distance matrix \(\mathbf D\), which is what we wanted to prove.

Finally, we note that \(\bar{\mathbf x}=n^{-1}\sum_{i=1}^n \mathbf x_i ={\bf 0}_k\), i.e. the sample mean vector of the new points is the zero vector, because \[\begin{equation} \bar{\mathbf x}=n^{-1}\mathbf X^\top {\bf 1}_n=\boldsymbol \Lambda^{1/2}\mathbf U^\top {\bf 1}_n={\bf 0}_k. \label{boldbarx} \end{equation}\] This is a consequence of the fact that \(\mathbf U^\top {\bf 1}_n={\bf 0}_k\), which is the case because the columns of \(\mathbf U\) are unit eigenvectors associated with strictly positive eigenvalues of \(\mathbf B=\mathbf U\boldsymbol \Lambda\mathbf U^\top\), while \({\bf 1}_n\) is an eigenvector of \(\mathbf B\) corresponding to a zero eigenvalue of \(\mathbf B\), hence \({\bf 1}_n\) is orthogonal to the columns of \(\mathbf U\).

Question 3

Suppose \(\mathbf X\) is a \(n \times p\) column centred data matrix. PCA looks at the spectral decomposition of the covariance matrix \(\frac{1}{n}\mathbf X^\top \mathbf X\), whereas MDS uses the spectral decomposition of the Gram matrix \(\mathbf X\mathbf X^\top\). Using the SVD for \(\mathbf X=\mathbf U\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\mathbf V^\top\), explain the relationship between these two methods.

Solution

Suppose \(\mathbf X\) has SVD \[\mathbf X= \mathbf U\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\mathbf V^\top\]

Then MDS looks at \[\mathbf X\mathbf X^\top = \mathbf U\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^2 \mathbf U^\top\] and so has eigenvalues given by the diagonal elements of \(\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\). The MDS coordinates are \(\mathbf U\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\).

In contrast, PCA uses the spectral decomposition of

\[\mathbf S=\frac{1}{n}\mathbf X^\top \mathbf X= \mathbf V\boldsymbol{\Sigma}^2 \mathbf V^\top\] so we can see the covariance matrix has the same eigenvalues as the Gram matrix. The PC scores are given by

\[\mathbf Y=\mathbf X\mathbf V=\mathbf U\boldsymbol{\Sigma}\] which is exactly the same as the MDS coordinates.

Question 4

This question is from the 2018-19 exam.

Solution

  1. \(\mathbf B= \mathbf H\mathbf A\mathbf H\) where \(a_{ij}=-\frac{1}{2}d_{ij}^2\). Here \(\mathbf H\) is the centering matrix: \[\mathbf H=\mathbf I-\frac{1}{n}\mathbf{1}\mathbf{1}^\top\] If \(\mathbf B\) has spectral decomposition \[\mathbf B= \sum_i \lambda_i \mathbf q_i \mathbf q_i^\top\] then the first \(k\) principal coordinates are given by \[\mathbf X= \begin{pmatrix}-&\mathbf x_1^\top&-\\& \vdots& \\-&\mathbf x_n^\top&-\end{pmatrix} = \begin{pmatrix}|&\ldots &|\\\mathbf v_1 &\ldots & \mathbf v_k\\|&\ldots &|\end{pmatrix}\operatorname{diag}\{\lambda_1^{0.5}, \ldots, \lambda_k^{0.5}\}\] assuming that \(\lambda_k >0\).

  2. No, \(\mathbf D\) is not Euclidean because it is has a negative eigenvalue, so \(\mathbf B\) is not positive definite.

The first two principal coordinates are

Q <- matrix(0.5*c(1,-1,1,-1,

Lambda <- diag(c(sqrt(2), sqrt(1)))

Question 5

Answer Q4 part (a) from the 2017-18 exam paper. Here, the ‘similarity matching coefficient’ is what we called the simple matching coefficient (SMC) in the notes.

Solution

For each pair of individuals, \(i\) and \(j\) say, form a \(2 \times 2\) table \[ \begin{array}{cccc} &1 &0\\ 1& a & b\\ 0& c & d \end{array} \] where \(a\) counts the number of attributes common to both individuals; \(b\) counts the number of attributes present in individual \(i\) but not \(j\); \(c\) counts the number of attributes \(j\) has that \(i\) does not; and
\(d\) counts the number of attributes which neither \(i\) of \(j\) have.

The simple/similarity matching coefficient for individuals \(i\) and \(j\) is then given by \[\sigma = \frac{a+d}{a+b+c+d}\] It measures the level of agreement between the two individuals.

If we calculate this for each pair of individuals we get

  • Person 1 and 2 \[ \begin{array}{cccc} &1 &0\\ 1& 3 & 1\\ 0& 1 & 1 \end{array} \qquad \sigma=\frac{2}{3} \]

  • Person 1 and 3 \[ \begin{array}{cccc} &1 &0\\ 1& 2 & 2\\ 0& 1 & 1 \end{array} \qquad \sigma=\frac{1}{2} \]

  • Person 1 and 4 \[ \begin{array}{cccc} &1 &0\\ 1& 1 & 3\\ 0& 0 & 2 \end{array} \qquad \sigma=\frac{1}{2} \]

  • Person 2 and 3 \[ \begin{array}{cccc} &1 &0\\ 1& 2 &2\\ 0& 1 & 1 \end{array} \qquad \sigma=\frac{1}{2} \]

  • Person 2 and 4 \[ \begin{array}{cccc} &1 &0\\ 1& 0 &4\\ 0& 1 & 1 \end{array} \qquad \sigma=\frac{1}{6} \]

  • Person 3 and 4 \[ \begin{array}{cccc} &1 &0\\ 1& 0 &3\\ 0& 1 & 2 \end{array} \qquad \sigma=\frac{1}{3} \]

  1. If \(\mathbf S\) is a similarity matrix, then we can convert it to dissimilarity matrix \(\mathbf D\) using the transformation \[d_{ij}=(s_{ii}+s_{jj}-2s_{ij})^{1/2}\]

Here it is appropriate to take \(s_{ii}=1\). This gives the dissimilarity matrix

S<- matrix(c(1, 2/3, 1/2, 1/2,
             2/3, 1, 1/2, 1/6,
             1/2, 1/2, 1, 1/3,
             1/2, 1/6, 1/3, 1), nr=4, byrow=T)
FtoD <- function(FF){
  n = dim(FF)[1]
  D <- matrix(nr=n,nc=n)
  for(ii in 1:n){
    for(jj in 1:n){
      D[ii,jj] <- sqrt(FF[ii,ii]+FF[jj,jj]-2*FF[ii,jj])
    }
  }
  return(D)
}

FtoD(S)

[2,] 0.8164966 0.0000000 1.000000 1.290994
[3,] 1.0000000 1.0000000 0.000000 1.154701
[4,] 1.0000000 1.2909944 1.154701 0.000000
  1. Given a distance matrix \(\mathbf D\), we define matrix \(\mathbf A\) with entries \(a_{ij} = -1/2 d_{ij}^2\), then calculate \(\mathbf B= \mathbf H\mathbf A\mathbf H\) where \(\mathbf H\) is the centering matrix.

If \(\mathbf B\) is positive semi-definite, then \(\mathbf D\) is a Euclidean distance matrix, but not if negative eigenvalues are present. In the latter case, we can use the positive definite part of \(\mathbf B\)

\[\mathbf B^+ = \sum_{i; \lambda_i \geq 0}\lambda_i \mathbf q_i \mathbf q_i^\top\]

One useful feature of MDS is that we can construct points in Euclidean space that have inter-point distances that are either approximately or exactly equal to the \(d_{ij}\)s. Two attractive features of MDS are i) dimension reduction and 2) visualizing datasets defined through a distance metric.
